TITLE: Fixing PyString::from_object in Rust to prevent out of bounds reads
DESCRIPTION: This code snippet fixes a security issue in PyString::from_object by properly null-terminating the encoding and errors strings. The fix ensures proper handling of these parameters before passing them to Python's API functions, preventing potential out of bounds memory reads.
SOURCE: https://github.com/PyO3/pyo3/blob/main/newsfragments/5008.fixed.md#2025-04-16_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: Rust
CODE:
```
fn from_object(ob: &PyAny, encoding: Option<&str>, errors: Option<&str>) -> PyResult<&'a PyString> {
    unsafe {
        // NOTE: These are using raw strings, do not want to increment the ref count.
        // Don't use opt.unwrap_or_else(|| std::ptr::null()) as that may cause out of bounds read.
        let encoding_cstring = encoding.map(|s| CString::new(s).unwrap());
        let errors_cstring = errors.map(|s| CString::new(s).unwrap());
        let encoding_ptr = encoding_cstring
            .as_ref()
            .map_or(std::ptr::null(), |s| s.as_ptr());
        let errors_ptr = errors_cstring
            .as_ref()
            .map_or(std::ptr::null(), |s| s.as_ptr());
        ob.py()
            .from_owned_ptr_or_err(ffi::PyUnicode_AsEncodedString(
                ob.as_ptr(),
                encoding_ptr,
                errors_ptr,
            ))
    }
}
```

